.TH edit 2m
.XI edit - "Buffer has be changed"
.SH NAME
edit \- Buffer has be changed
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "edit Mode"
.sp
\fB\&e\fR\& \- mode line letters.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B edit
mode  indicated  that the buffer has been  edited.  Many  commands  and typing
\&'edit' the current  buffer,  automatically  setting this mode. Commands  which
save these edits, such as
.Ht save-buffer 2 ,
automatically remove this mode.
.PP
A '*'  character,  3  characters  from  the  left on the mode  line is used to
indicate that this mode is set, see
.Ht $mode-line 5 .
.Ht list-buffers 2
also  displays  the state of this mode in its  output, as a '*' in the  second
column.
.PP
When this mode is set and
.Ht undo 2m
mode is enabled, the
.Ht undo 2
command can be used to undo all edits and the removal of this mode.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.na
